Here's a multi-form question based on the provided documentation:

Question: A system administrator is trying to set up SSH key authentication on a Synology NAS running DSM 6.1. Which of the following command sequences will correctly set the necessary permissions for the user's home directory and SSH files?

A) chmod 755 $homedir;
   chmod 755 $homedir/.ssh/;
   chmod 644 $homedir/.ssh/authorized_keys;

B) sudo chown root:root $homedir -R;
   chmod 700 $homedir;
   chmod 700 $homedir/.ssh/;
   chmod 600 $homedir/.ssh/authorized_keys;

C) homedir=$(eval echo ~$USER);
   sudo chown $USER:users $homedir -R;
   chmod 700 $homedir;
   chmod 700 $homedir/.ssh/;
   chmod 600 $homedir/.ssh/authorized_keys;

D) homedir=$(eval echo ~$USER);
   sudo chown $USER:root $homedir -R;
   chmod 755 $homedir;
   chmod 755 $homedir/.ssh/;
   chmod 644 $homedir/.ssh/authorized_keys;

Correct Answer: C

Explanation: The correct sequence of commands (C) sets the appropriate permissions and ownership for SSH key authentication on a Synology NAS. It sets the home directory and .ssh folder to 700 (rwx------) and the authorized_keys file to 600 (rw-------), which are the recommended permissions for secure SSH access. It also ensures that the user owns their home directory and its contents, with the group set to "users". Options A and D use less restrictive permissions (755 and 644) which are not recommended for SSH security. Option B incorrectly sets the ownership to root, which would prevent the user from accessing their own home directory.
